<span id="freeTextContainer16428894484762715469">After watching a ton of movies based on the Amityville story I figured it was about time I read the book. I find the whole Lutz family ordeal completely fascinating although I do doubt if it’s 100% true. This book just reinforced those thoughts. I still love it and find it wildly interesting but did it all really happen? That aside, this one hell of a killer ghost/poltergeist story. I’m just so intrigued by the thought of supernatural beings acting out in such a vicious way because I have experi</span>
  <span id="freeText16428894484762715469" style="display:none">After watching a ton of movies based on the Amityville story I figured it was about time I read the book. I find the whole Lutz family ordeal completely fascinating although I do doubt if it’s 100% true. This book just reinforced those thoughts. I still love it and find it wildly interesting but did it all really happen? That aside, this one hell of a killer ghost/poltergeist story. I’m just so intrigued by the thought of supernatural beings acting out in such a vicious way because I have experienced ghosts personally and they were just playful more than scary in any way. The whole idea of ghosts in general fascinates me and I think that’s why the Amityville story captures my attention so much despite doubting it’s truth, because what if?! All that aside, while I did thoroughly enjoy reading the story in print form the writing itself left something to be desired. It was just so dry and emotionless and dragged down such a big production of a story. It’s still worth a read though if you’re anywhere near as intrigued by ghosts or this story as I am!</span>
  <a data-text-id="16428894484762715469" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
